{"query": "What management techniques involving tree removal can be used to increase forest structural diversity and what are their effects?", "summary": "Several tree removal management techniques can be used to increase forest structural diversity with varying effects on different forest components. Shelterwood harvesting is an effective technique that resulted in higher plant diversity, lower grass cover and higher density of tree species compared with clearcutting (Action 1214), and six of seven studies found it increased abundance, species richness and diversity of understory plants, as well as the growth and survival rate of young trees (Action 1223). Group-selection harvesting showed mixed results, with four of eight studies finding it increased cover and diversity of understory plants and the density of young trees, while two studies found it decreased understory species richness and biomass (Action 1224). 

Tree thinning is another effective technique where seventeen of 25 studies found that thinning trees in forests increased the density and cover of understory plants, and thirteen of 19 studies found it increased species richness and diversity of understory plants (Action 1211). Thinning by girdling (cutting rings around tree trunks) increased understory plant species richness, diversity and cover (Action 1226). General logging and tree removal within forests showed more variable effects, with five of ten studies finding it increased the density and cover of understory plants, and four of seven studies finding it increased species richness and diversity of understory plants (Action 1273).

Selective or reduced impact logging had different effects on wildlife, with one review of 41 studies finding that reduced impact logging had a smaller effect on bat abundance than conventional logging (Action 989). Thinning within forests also benefited other wildlife, with five of six studies finding higher overall bat activity in thinned or thinned and burned forest than unthinned forest (Action 991), and four studies finding that coniferous woodland thinned with prescribed burning, mulching or nearby felling had greater species richness of butterflies than unmanaged woodland (Action 3940).", "action_ids": ["1214","1223","1224","1211","1226","1273","989","991","3940"]}

